{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01RaBpX1txwDbdqoeC1LbyVY","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see what's happening. Pod 1 is in CrashLoopBackOff and it received a SIGTERM (terminated signal). The logs show:\n- \"received signal 'terminated'\" - pod 1 was killed\n- \"ranges.unavailable: 4\" and \"ranges.underreplicated: 4\"\n- 4 liveness heartbeat failures\n\nThe cluster is already initialized (it knows about n1, n2, n3 from previous state), but the pods are failing. \n\nPod 1 is crashing. Let me check why it's crashing in more detail - it seems to be getting killed. Let me look at the events more carefully.\nThe liveness probe is configured to fail after 6 consecutive failures with a 10-second period between checks. So after about 60 seconds of the health endpoint not responding, Kubernetes kills the pod. That's what's triggering the SIGTERM and the CrashLoopBackOff cycle.\n\nThe real issue is a quorum problem - the original cluster had 3 nodes, but now only pod 0 is stable while pods 1 and 2 keep crashing. With 3 nodes, Raft needs at least 2 healthy nodes to maintain quorum and allow writes. Pod 0 has been running for 17 minutes but can't get heartbeats from the other nodes, so the cluster is stuck and can't process operations, which is why the health checks are failing. The liveness probe timing makes sense—30 seconds initial delay plus six 10-second intervals gives about 90 seconds before termination, which matches what I'm seeing. The issue is likely that the HTTP server isn't starting quickly enough on these nodes with existing data, so even the basic /health endpoint fails before the delay window closes. Node 2 was actually functioning and processing operations before Kubernetes killed it, so the nodes aren't fundamentally broken—they're just getting terminated before they can fully initialize.\n\nLooking at the current state, pod 0 and pod 2 are running but not ready, while pod 1 is stuck in CrashLoopBackOff with five restarts. The cluster can't stabilize until pod 1 stops crashing, which means I need to figure out why it keeps failing to start.\n\nThe liveness probe is configured with a 30-second initial delay and checks every 10 seconds, allowing up to 6 failures before killing the pod. That gives roughly 90 seconds before termination. The probe hits the /health endpoint, which should return 200 as long as the server process is running, regardless of cluster connectivity. So if the node is crashing with SIGTERM, it's likely the probe is failing because the server isn't responding in time, or there's something else preventing the node from staying alive during that initial startup window.\n\nLet me examine the crash logs to see what's actually happening with the process.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1937,"cache_read_input_tokens":37971,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1937},"output_tokens":36,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4d6ce834-1657-4ba5-a1f5-1a66b0295e32","uuid":"747ccf9f-2a75-4bb3-97e4-1830ce65d38b","request_id":"req_011CcamhYSvstX1ffaSStyve"}
