{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01KeYmgr1ug9fwbkeRpsGFCD","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture:\n\n**Root cause:** CockroachDB cluster is stuck in a state where:\n1. `crdb-cluster-0` (n1) and `crdb-cluster-2` (n3) are Running but NOT ready\n2. `crdb-cluster-1` (n2) is in CrashLoopBackOff (5 restarts, 88s into backoff delay)\n\nThe critical issue is the quorum loss. Looking at the raft status in node 3's logs:\n```\nr2:/System/NodeLiveness{-Max} [(n1,s1):1, (n2,s2):2, next=3, gen=2]: lost quorum (down: (n2,s2):2)\n```\n\nThe NodeLiveness range only has 2 replicas across n1 and n2, so when n2 goes down in CrashLoopBackOff, the range loses quorum and becomes unavailable. This prevents the entire cluster from functioning since NodeLiveness is a critical system range.\n\nThe real issue is that the cluster was set up as a 3-node cluster, but the NodeLiveness range somehow ended up with just 2 replicas instead of 3, leaving n3 without a replica for this essential range. With n2 down, n1 can't reach quorum to update liveness heartbeats, which causes all nodes to appear dead to each other. So the NodeLiveness range should have 3 replicas in a 3-node cluster, but it only has 2—likely because the cluster was recently expanded from 2 nodes to 3, and the rebalancing hasn't happened yet. The critical issue is that n2 being down means we've lost quorum on NodeLiveness, which paralyzes the entire cluster, so getting n2 back online is the immediate priority.\n\nLooking at the liveness probe configuration, I notice the pods have different settings—pod 2 has a particularly aggressive setup with only a 1-second timeout and a 3-failure threshold, meaning it'll kill the pod after about 45 seconds if the HTTP server isn't responding. That's a very tight window for the server to come up, and the short timeout makes it easy to fail on transient delays.\n\nI'm considering three approaches: waiting for Kubernetes to gradually increase the backoff timer (which can take up to 300 seconds), deleting and recreating pod 1 to reset the backoff, or temporarily loosening the liveness probe constraints. The key insight is that the /health endpoint just checks if the HTTP server is running—it doesn't validate cluster quorum—so once the server starts, the probe should pass. But something in the startup sequence is taking longer than the probe allows.\n\nLooking at the connection refused error and the restart history, the HTTP server isn't binding to port 8080 within the 30-second initial delay. The pod has already crashed 5 times and is currently in a backoff period waiting for the next restart attempt. So the cockroach server needs to start listening on port 8080 within that 45-second window. Looking back at the pod events, the readiness probe failed quickly with connection refused errors, but the liveness probe is what actually killed the pods after accumulating failures. I'm noticing the probe configurations differ between pods—pod 0 has a longer timeout and more allowed failures compared to pod 1 and pod 2.\n\nThe key difference is in the liveness probe settings: pod 0 allows 6 failures at 10-second intervals after a 30-second delay, giving it about 90 seconds total before termination, while pods 1 and 2 only allow 3 failures at 5-second intervals, which means they get killed around the 45-second mark. This suggests the StatefulSet spec was modified between deployments.\n\nBut looking back at pod 1's logs, it was actually running and handling SQL operations before getting terminated, so the HTTP server did come up successfully at some point. The aggressive probe settings on the newer pods might be causing premature restarts if the server takes longer to fully stabilize. The real issue is that node 2 is down and holds replicas for the NodeLiveness range, so the remaining nodes can't reach quorum. I need to get node 2 back online. Since it's stuck in CrashLoopBackOff, deleting the pod will reset the backoff timer and force the StatefulSet to recreate it immediately—once all three nodes are running again, the cluster should stabilize. Pod 1 should restart in about 72 seconds once the backoff timer expires, which should allow the cluster to regain quorum. Looking more closely at the logs, I see that pod 1 received SIGTERM in its last run—Kubernetes killed it after the liveness probe failed three times in succession (at 30s, 35s, and 40s intervals based on the probe configuration).\n\nThe puzzle is that pod 1's earlier logs show it was running long enough to execute SQL work, meaning the HTTP server did come up at some point. Yet it still got terminated. Now pod 1 is stuck in CrashLoopBackOff, waiting for the backoff period to expire before Kubernetes attempts another restart.\n\nMy best move is to delete pod 1 outright so the StatefulSet recreates it with a fresh start, bypassing the backoff delay. I should also examine the StatefulSet's liveness probe configuration—if the 45-second kill window is too tight, I might need to adjust the probe settings to give the container more breathing room.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5705,"cache_read_input_tokens":44821,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":5705},"output_tokens":20,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4d6ce834-1657-4ba5-a1f5-1a66b0295e32","uuid":"774db990-fba3-4c9b-a96c-3d5bbf464a5c","request_id":"req_011CcamnqgQe1Ucmx291xZ82"}
